s countries does that the Quality of Life Measures capture livability slightly better than they capture life ability.</strong></p>\r\n                            </article>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </section>\r\n                    <a name="statistical-analysis"></a>\r\n                    <section class="post standard">\r\n                        <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                            <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                                <h2 id="statistical_analysis">Statistical Analysis</h2>\r\n                                <hr>\r\n                            </header>\r\n                            <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                                <p>The literature review and empirical meta-analysis identified an initial set of recurring variables found to impact happiness and life satisfaction (see the Project’s literature reviews here). A Principle Component Analysis of approximately one hundred variables in the World Values Survey was used to identify the underlying attributes of these factors. The complete set of factors identified through this analysis was incorporated in an Ordinary Least Squares regression controlling for other factors. The regression analysis revealed a set of variables with a significant positive impact on Quality of Life Measures. These findings were subjected to several forms of sensitivity analysis. The significant factors and controls were grouped together in six dimensions according to their weights and theoretical considerations to form the six dimensions of Quality of Life </p>\r\n                            </article>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </section>\r\n                    <a name="creating-and-validating-the-dimensions"></a>\r\n                    <section class="post standard">\r\n                        <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                            <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                                <h2 id="creating_and_validation_the_dimensions">Creating and Validating the Dimensions</h2>\r\n                                <hr>\r\n                            </header>\r\n                            <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                                <p>The six dimensions WERE RECONSTRUCTED using a combination of self-reported and what the academic literature terms objective indicators to correct for the disadvantages of each. The specific indicators were chosen based on statistical analysis, previous findings in the literature, comparability across time and geographical areas, availability, and source reputation in order to ensure the highest possible level of quality. Because previous research has found that outcomes relative to expectations are strong predictors of Quality of Life, changes in some variables were selected in addition to actual levels.</p>\r\n                                <p>The indicators selected were tested analytically through the methods of Confirmatory Factor Analysis, Average Variance Extracted, and the Cronbach’s Alpha method.</p>\r\n                                <p>Indicators were normalized using an approach modeled on the original Human Development measurements. Goalposts were chosen to represent the maximum and minimum values for each indicator, either from the source or from an analysis of the existing observations. Individual scores were calculated using a linearization between the two goalposts. Once the scores for indicators were obtained, they were aggregated hierarchically, with each score equaling either the score of the associated indicator or the average of the scores one level below it. The score for Dimension 1 is therefore the average of the score for Components 1A and 1B while the score for Component 1A is the average of the score for Subcomponents 1Ai and 1Aii.</p>\r\n                                <p>Additional research and analysis relative to the project can be found <a href="<?php echo home_url(); ?>/research">here</a>.</p>\r\n                            </article>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </section>\r\n                </div>\r\n                <a name="dimensions"></a>\r\n                    <section class="carousel dimensions">\r\n        <div class="row">\r\n            <header class="title-group">\r\n                <h2 id="six_dimensions">The Six Dimensions of Quality of Life Measures</h2>\r\n                <hr/>\r\n                <p>\r\n                    The Quality of Life Measures compiled data from a whole host of sources to compose this United States measurements. Various sources include (but are not limited to) the U.S. Census, the Bureau of Labor Statistics, Gallup, and the National Center for Educational Statistics.\r\n                </p>\r\n            </header>\r\n\r\n            <div class="slide-toggle clearfix">\r\n                <a href="#" class="us selected">U.S. Measurements</a><a href="#" class="world">World Measurements</a>\r\n            </div>\r\n\r\n            <ul class="slide-list">\r\n                <li class="slide us">\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns opportunity">\r\n                            <h3>Opportunity</h3>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Poverty<br />\r\n                                Employment<br />\r\n                                Community Vitality<br />\r\n                                Education</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns health_and_environment">\r\n                            <h3>Health &#038; Environment</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Physical Health<br />\r\n                                Mental Health<br />\r\n                                Environmental Health</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns freedom">\r\n                            <h3>Freedom</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Personal Freedom<br />\r\n                                Economic Freedom</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns community_and_relationships">\r\n                            <h3>Community &#038; Relationships</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Community Life<br />\r\n                                Family Life</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns living_standard">\r\n                            <h3>Living Standard</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Current Living Standard<br />\r\n                                Improvement in Living Standard</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns peace_and_security">\r\n                            <h3>Peace &#038; Security</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Violent Crime Rate<br />\r\n                                Property Crime Rate<br />\r\n                                Perceived Local Safety<br />\r\n                                Trust</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </li>\r\n                     <li class="slide world">\r\n\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns opportunity">\r\n                            <h3>Opportunity</h3>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Poverty<br />\r\n                                Employment<br />\r\n                                Community Basics<br />\r\n                                Entrepreneurship</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns health_and_environment">\r\n                            <h3>Health &#038; Environment</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Physical Health<br />\r\n                                Mental Health<br />\r\n                                Environmental Health</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns freedom">\r\n                            <h3>Freedom</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Political Freedom<br />\r\n                                Civil Liberties<br />\r\n                                Religious Freedom<br />\r\n                                Economic Freedom<br />\r\n                                Perceived Freedom</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns community_and_relationships">\r\n                            <h3>Community &#038; Relationships</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Community Life<br />\r\n                                Family Life</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns living_standard">\r\n                            <h3>Living Standard</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Current Living Standard<br />\r\n                                Improvement in Living Standard</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns peace_and_security">\r\n                            <h3>Peace &#038; Security</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Violence and Ethnic Warfare<br />\r\n                                Human Rights Violations<br />\r\n                                Corruption in Business & Government<br />\r\n                                Trust in National Institutions<br />\r\n                                Law and Order<br />\r\n                                Bureaucracy Quality</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </li>\r\n                </ul>\r\n                <p>Learn more about the sources of these measurements.”</p>\r\n                <a class="btn flat gray download pdf variables" href="<?php echo get_template_directory_uri(); ?>/pdf/Quality_of_Life_Variables_US_Measures.pdf" target="_blank" style="background-image: url(&#39;<?php echo get_template_directory_uri(); ?>/images/icons/pdf.png&#39;);">Download U.S. Variables</a>\r\n\r\n            </div>\r\n        </section>\r\n            <div class="row">\r\n                <a name="glossary"></a>\r\n                <section class="glossary">\r\n                    <header class="title-group">\r\n                    <h2>Glossary</h2>\r\n                    <hr>\r\n                    </header>\r\n                    <div class="row">\r\n                        <div class="glossary-item-container large-12 medium-12 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Component</h3>\r\n                                <p>The different qualities of a particular dimension. For example, the components of the freedom dimension are civil liberties, economic freedom, political freedom, religious freedom, and perception of freedom.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Component Score</h3>\r\n                                <p>The value obtained from averaging the scores for subcomponents within a particular component for a country or U.S. state.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Dimension</h3>\r\n                                <p>One of the six key elements of Quality of Life Measures(i.e., Living Standard, Health &amp; Environment, Freedom, Opportunity, Community &amp; Relationships, or Peace &amp; Security) as defined by the Measures of Quality of Life.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Dimension Score</h3>\r\n                                <p>The value obtained from averaging the scores for components within a particular dimension for a country or U.S. state.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Happiness</h3>\r\n                                <p>The range of positive feelings, stretching from contentment to joy, that a person experiences.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Life Satisfaction</h3>\r\n                                <p>A person’s cognitive, evaluative reflection of that individual’s life as a whole.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Life ability</h3>\r\n                                <p>A measurement of an individual’s internal capacity to be happy and satisfied and his or her adeptness at taking advantage of the external environment.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Livability</h3>\r\n                                <p>A measurement of how the external, societal environment enables Quality of Life Measures.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Normalization</h3>\r\n                                <p>The method used to reconcile variables that are based on different units of measurement.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Objective Variables</h3>\r\n                                <p>Quantifiable social or economic variables that are based on specific standards and reported by outside observers.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Score</h3>\r\n                                <p>The normalized value used to estimate each variable. The variable scores are aggregated for subcomponents, components, and dimensions and result in the final measurement of the Quality of Life of a country or U.S. state.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Subcomponent</h3>\r\n                                <p>One of two or more factors of a component. For example, the Living Standard dimension consists of the two components of current living standard and improvement in living standard. The improvement in living standard component includes the 5-year growth in GDP and perceptions of improvement in living standard as subcomponents.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Subcomponent Score</h3>\r\n                                <p>The value obtained from averaging the scores for variables within a particular subcomponent for a country or U.S. state.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Subjective Variables</h3>\r\n                                <p>Variables that are individually perceived and obtained through self-reported methods.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Variable</h3>\r\n                                <p>One of many attributes used to characterize a certain aspect of the Quality of Life Measures of a country or U.S. state. There are 50 variables in the World measurements and 42 in the U.S. measurements.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Variable Score</h3>\r\n                                <p>The normalized value used to estimate each attribute of the Quality of Life Measures of a country or U.S. state.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Quality of Life Measures Score</h3>\r\n                                <p>The value obtained from averaging the six dimension scores for a country or U.S. state.<br>\r\n                                Quality of Life Measures consists of the two underlying concepts of happiness and life satisfaction and emanates both from societal factors (livability) and from the internal personal dynamics that enable the individual to benefit from the societal environment (life ability).</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n            </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n', 'Quality of Life Measures', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '224-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-03-07 07:42:20', '2015-03-07 07:42:20', '', 224, 'http://localhost/life-measures-wordpress/224-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
	(359, 1, '2015-03-07 08:39:43', '2015-03-07 08:39:43', '<body id="data" class="page page-id-17 page-parent page-template-default win8.1 chrome chrome-0">\r\n<section class="intro-image" style="background-image: url(&#39;<?php echo get_template_directory_uri(); ?>/images/cki-template11-headers-getdata.jpg&#39;);">\r\n                <header>\r\n                    <h1>Download and Interact with the Project’s Data</h1>\r\n                    <hr>\r\n                </header>\r\n            </section>\r\n            <div id="content" class="row">\r\n                <a name="the-data-for-the-indices-of-well-being-are-available-in-four-different-sets-to-suit-different-research-needs"></a>\r\n                <section class="post box post-347 standard_post  large-6 medium-6 small-12 columns">\r\n                    <div class="border row clearfix">\r\n                        <header>\r\n                            <h2>The data for the Measures of Quality of Life are available in three different sets to suit different research needs.</h2>\r\n                        </header>\r\n                        <article>\r\n                            <ul>\r\n                                <li>The Standard dataset interpolates missing scores between data points, but it does not back-fill or forward-fill missing values.</li>\r\n                                <li>The Chain-linked dataset uses chain-linking to create a series for overall Quality of Life and each of the dimensions appropriate for time-series analysis.</li>\r\n                                <li>The Raw dataset provides all input data used to create, with no alterations.</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            <p>In addition, the data can be downloaded through a REST-ful API, which allows for the creation of custom subsets of the Completed dataset.</p>\r\n                        </article>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n                                   