r use of the University Site, we reserve the right to use any information we have collected about you in connection with any efforts we make or made by any of our agents on our behalf.</p>\r\n                        <h3>User Comments</h3>\r\n                        <p>Please be aware that any personal information you provide in connection with comments you contribute to the University Site or any other interactive features we may offer will be visible to other users and visitors to those websites.</p>\r\n                        <h3>Polls, Surveys, Sweepstakes, Giveaways, Contests, and Promotions</h3>\r\n                        <p>University may request information from you via online polls, surveys, sweepstakes, giveaways, or contests. Participation in polls, surveys, sweepstakes, giveaways, or contests is voluntary; you have a choice whether or not to disclose information required to enter. Information requested may include personal contact information such as your name, address, phone number, mobile phone number, email address, username, birth date, and/or similar information. We may share this information with our affiliates, vendors, and other organizations or entities. Contact information will be used to notify winners and award prizes. Contact information may also be used to contact you with further information about University, as well as the information about third parties whose activities relate to the educational mission of University.  Survey information, and related information you provide to University, may be used for the purposes of monitoring or improving use of and satisfaction with the University Site.</p>\r\n                        <h3>Online Advertisements</h3>\r\n                        <p>University may run online advertisements on third-party websites to attract visitors to the University Site or to alert the public to opportunities related to our educational mission.  Our advertising vendors may use cookies and clear GIFs on the University Site and on the third-party sites on which our ads appear, which allow the advertising vendor to track certain information about user behavior, such as “click-stream data.”  Any use of information by an advertising vendor is governed by their terms of use and privacy policy, so you should familiarize yourself with these policies prior to responding to online advertisements.</p>\r\n                        <h3>Text Messages and Other Points of Contact</h3>\r\n                        <p>If you sign up to receive text messages from us, University may collect, store, and use your mobile phone number to send you such messages.  We may also collect and store other personally identifiable information, such as your name, address, phone number, mobile phone number, email address, username, and/or similar information you may opt to provide to us.  If you provide us with your email address, we may use it to send you email newsletters and updates from University.  In addition, as noted above, we may share this information with our affiliates, vendors, and other organizations or entities.</p>\r\n                        <h3>Email Newsletters and Updates</h3>\r\n                        <p>If you sign up to receive email newsletters and updates from University and its affiliates and/or organizations that aid or share University’s educational mission, we may collect, store, and use your email address to send you information from University. We may also collect and store other personally identifiable information you give University, including but not limited to your name, address, phone number, mobile phone number, email address, username, birth date, and/or similar information you may opt to provide us. If you provide us with your mobile phone number, University may use it to send you text messages. In addition, as noted above, we may share this information with our affiliates, vendors, and other organizations or entities to advance University’s educational mission.</p>\r\n                        <h3>Employment Opportunities</h3>\r\n                        <p>You may choose to apply for employment, an internship position, or to participate in an educational program with University through online application forms we may provide, or by sending us, by email or otherwise, a resume and letter (containing personally identifiable information). Any information you provide to us in this regard may be viewed by University and any third parties who assist University in recruiting, selection, and similar services for the purpose of evaluating your application and/or responding to your employment-related inquiry. University may share any or all of the materials you submit related to job opportunities with affiliates and other organizations in furtherance of University’s educational mission.</p>\r\n                        <h3>Other Communications</h3>\r\n                        <p>You may decide to contact University, by email or otherwise, with other inquiries or to provide feedback. Any personally identifiable information you provide in connection with such inquiries or feedback may be collected and used by University for the purpose of processing and responding to your inquiries or feedback.</p>\r\n                    </article>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n                <section class="post standard">\r\n                    <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                        <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <h2>Non-Personally Identifiable Information</h2>\r\n                            <hr>\r\n                        </header>\r\n                        <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <p>University gathers certain broad information about the use of the University Site, including the number of unique visitors, the frequency with which they visit, and the programs and services preferred. We look at the data in summary form, rather than on an individual basis. We gather this information so we can learn how many people visit the University Site, see which pages are the most and least viewed, identify which websites are referring visitors to the University Site, and related information. The data helps us determine the extent to which visitors use certain parts of the University Site. Thus, we use this information to help us in restructuring the University Site to better meet the needs of our users.</p>\r\n                            <p>In connection with these activities we may use some of the below mentioned tools.</p>\r\n                            <h3>Cookies</h3>\r\n                            <p>We use cookies to track usage and to enhance the efficiency of user interaction with the University Site, gain insight into and customize your use of the University Site, and help maintain the University Site’s proper operation. Cookies are small files placed on the hard drive of your computer; each website can send its own cookie to your browser if your browser preferences allow it. You can configure your browser to accept all cookies, reject all cookies, or notify you when a cookie is set. (Each browser is different, so check the “Help” menu of your browser to learn how to change your cookie preferences.) You are always free to decline our cookies if your browser permits, although that may prevent you from using certain features on the University Site. Please note that several companies offer utilities designed to help you visit websites anonymously.</p>\r\n                            <p>Generally, we will not allow third parties to place any cookies, web beacons, or other similar devices on the University Site. University may allow third parties to place cookies on the University Site, such as the below-referenced Google Analytics, in order to improve services University provides to advance our educational mission. We do not control devices that may be placed on the University Site by third parties. University is not responsible for any other websites accessible from or linked to this website, including their privacy policies or information collection practices.</p>\r\n                            <h3>Google Analytics</h3>\r\n                            <p>University uses Google Analytics, a service that uses cookies and tracking code to analyze how visitors use the University Site. The information collected (including your browser and operating system, IP address, pages visited on our website, and time spent here) is transmitted to and stored by Google. Google uses this information to evaluate visitors’ use of the University Site in an aggregate manner. Google compiles reports on website activity and provides other related services. Google may transfer this information to third parties that process information on its behalf or as required by law. Please take the time to familiarize yourself with Google’s privacy policy.</p>\r\n                            <h3>IP Addresses</h3>\r\n                            <p>We collect and analyze traffic on the University Site by keeping track of the IP addresses of our visitors. An IP address is the unique numeric identifier assigned to each computer browser accessing the internet. An IP address, by itself, cannot identify you personally.  When combined with other information provided by your Internet Service Provider (“ISP”), however, your IP address can be used to identify the computer originating a message.</p>\r\n                        </article>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n                <section class="post standard">\r\n                    <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                        <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <h2>Modifications to this Privacy Policy</h2>\r\n                            <hr>\r\n                        </header>\r\n                        <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <p>We may amend or change this Privacy Policy at any time. In the event of any material change, University will post a clear notice of such a revision to this Policy on the University Site or email you such notice at an email address you have provided to University.</p>\r\n                        </article>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n                <section class="post standard">\r\n                    <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                        <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <h2>How to Update Your Information, Unsubscribe, or Contact Us</h2>\r\n                            <hr>\r\n                        </header>\r\n                        <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <p>We wish to maintain your information accurately, and to allow you to make choices about how we use it.  If you wish to review the contact information we have on file for you, correct your contact information, provide a change of address, or inform us how you wish your contact information to be used, please contact our staff. You may contact us by email at: <!-- <a href="mailto:email@charleskochUniversity.org">email@charleskochUniversity.org</a></p> -->\r\n                            <p>If you do not want to receive any email from us in the future, click the “unsubscribe” reference in any email we send you. Otherwise, you may email us at<strong> (Email here) </strong><!-- <a href="mailto:email@charleskochUniversity.org">email@charleskochUniversity.org</a> --> with the subject line reading “UNSUBSCRIBE” to complete the opt-out process, or send a letter to the below address requesting that we unsubscribe you from our contact lists. Note that absent a specific request your records will remain in our database, but your email address and other information used to contact you will be deactivated.</p>\r\n                        </article>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n                <section class="post standard">\r\n                    <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                        <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <h2>How We Collect Information</h2>\r\n                            <hr>\r\n                        </header>\r\n                        <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <p>The University collects both personally identifiable information and non-personally identifiable information from you in a number of ways. Personally identifiable information is generally information that identifies you, such as your name, telephone number, postal address, email address, and birth date. Non-personally identifiable information is information that does not personally identify you, including anonymous information and aggregate data. The University uses this information to understand better how visitors use the University Site, research our visitors’ demographics, interests, and behavior, provide visitors with customized services and information, improve our promotional and outreach efforts, and for other similar purposes.</p>\r\n                        </article>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n                <section class="post standard">\r\n                    <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                        <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <h2>Complaints or Questions</h2>\r\n                            <hr>\r\n                        </header>\r\n                        <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                            \r\n                            \r\n                        </article>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n                <section class="post standard">\r\n                    <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                        <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <h2>A Special Note about Children</h2>\r\n                            <hr>\r\n                        </header>\r\n                        <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <p>We encourage everyone to visit the University Site and learn about the University. Children, however, are not eligible to register to use the services of the University, and we ask that minors not submit any personal information to us. If you are a minor, you may use this service only in conjunction with a parent or guardian. Parents or guardians should become knowledgeable about software and other tools so they can assure that children’s use of the Internet reflects parental preferences and requirements.</p>\r\n                        </article>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n                <section class="post standard">\r\n                    <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                        <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <h2>Security</h2>\r\n                            <hr>\r\n                        </header>\r\n                        <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <p>Although the University Site has certain security measures in place to protect the loss, misuse, and alteration of the information you provide, no email or web transmission is completely secure against interception or incorrect routing. Thus, there is always the risk that unauthorized persons may access or use your personally identifiable information.  If you are worried because your communication is very sensitive, do not send it electronically. Please consider this prior to submitting any information to us via the University Site. You use the University Site and send us such information at your own risk.</p>\r\n                            <p>Although we take reasonable measure to protect your privacy on the University Site, we need your help.  You have control over your own privacy. Think carefully before providing any personal or financial information online. If you desire to remain anonymous when you write to us or send us submissions you should not tell us your name, the names of other users, or of your friends. To fully protect your privacy, you should try to exclude any information that you think may identify you or others.</p>\r\n                            <p>Remember that we cannot protect your privacy once you leave the University Site, such as by hyperlink. We do not control the privacy policies of other websites. So when you visit other websites, check each site’s privacy policy, and be careful about the information you submit or share. In addition, you should only forward our email messages or other website information (such as our job postings) to others through the buttons or links provided within the email or the University Site. When you use your email system’s forwarding capabilities, others may be able to take actions in your name and/or access your personal information.</p>\r\n                        </article>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n            </div>', 'Privacy Statement', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '222-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-03-10 11:29:34', '2015-03-10 11:29:34', '', 222, 'http://localhost/life-measures-wordpress/222-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
	(614, 1, '2015-03-10 11:52:56', '2015-03-10 11:52:56', '<body id="indices" class="page page-id-15 page-parent page-template page-template-page-indices-php win8 chrome chrome-0">\r\n<section class="intro-image" style="background-image: url(&#39;<?php echo get_template_directory_uri(); ?>/images/cki-template11-headers-indicies.jpg&#39;);">\r\n                <header>\r\n                    <h1>Constructing the Quality of Life Measures</h1>\r\n                    <hr>\r\n                </header>\r\n            </section>\r\n            <div id="content">\r\n                <div class="row">\r\n                    <a name="constructing-the-indices"></a>\r\n                    <section class="post standard">\r\n                        <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                            <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <h2 id="contstructing_the_indices">Constructing the Measures</h2>\r\n                            <hr>\r\n                            </header>\r\n                            <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                                <p>Drawing on a long literature, beginning with ancient Greek philosophical works and ending with modern economic and psychological empirical studies, the Quality of Life Project defines Wellbeing and Quality of Life as consisting of two parts: happiness, understood as the range of positive feelings stretching from contentment to joy that a person experiences at any given time, and life satisfaction, understood as a cognitive evaluation of one’s life as a whole. Additionally, the Project found that personal wellbeing derives largely from two broad sources: livability, the external factors that inhibit or enable Quality of Life, and life ability, the internal capabilities that allow individuals to take advantage of their environment.</p>\r\n                                <p><strong>Issues of Data-availability across countries does that the Quality of Life Measures capture livability slightly better than they capture life ability.</strong></p>\r\n                            </article>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </section>\r\n                    <a name="statistical-analysis"></a>\r\n                    <section class="post standard">\r\n                        <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                            <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                                <h2 id="statistical_analysis">Statistical Analysis</h2>\r\n                                <hr>\r\n                            </header>\r\n                            <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                                <p>The literature review and empirical meta-analysis identified an initial set of recurring variables found to impact happiness and life satisfaction (see the Project’s literature reviews here). A Principle Component Analysis of approximately one hundred variables in the World Values Survey was used to identify the underlying attributes of these factors. The complete set of factors identified through this analysis was incorporated in an Ordinary Least Squares regression controlling for other factors. The regression analysis revealed a set of variables with a significant positive impact on Quality of Life Measures. These findings were subjected to several forms of sensitivity analysis. The significant factors and controls were grouped together in six dimensions according to their weights and theoretical considerations to form the six dimensions of Quality of Life </p>\r\n                            </article>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </section>\r\n                    <a name="creating-and-validating-the-dimensions"></a>\r\n                    <section class="post standard">\r\n                        <div class="row clearfix">\r\n                            <header class="large-3 medium-3 small-12 columns">\r\n                                <h2 id="creating_and_validation_the_dimensions">Creating and Validating the Dimensions</h2>\r\n                                <hr>\r\n                            </header>\r\n                            <article class="large-8 large-offset-1 medium-8 medium-offset-1 small-12 columns">\r\n                                <p>The six dimensions WERE RECONSTRUCTED using a combination of self-reported and what the academic literature terms objective indicators to correct for the disadvantages of each. The specific indicators were chosen based on statistical analysis, previous findings in the literature, comparability across time and geographical areas, availability, and source reputation in order to ensure the highest possible level of quality. Because previous research has found that outcomes relative to expectations are strong predictors of Quality of Life, changes in some variables were selected in addition to actual levels.</p>\r\n                                <p>The indicators selected were tested analytically through the methods of Confirmatory Factor Analysis, Average Variance Extracted, and the Cronbach’s Alpha method.</p>\r\n                                <p>Indicators were normalized using an approach modeled on the original Human Development measurements. Goalposts were chosen to represent the maximum and minimum values for each indicator, either from the source or from an analysis of the existing observations. Individual scores were calculated using a linearization between the two goalposts. Once the scores for indicators were obtained, they were aggregated hierarchically, with each score equaling either the score of the associated indicator or the average of the scores one level below it. The score for Dimension 1 is therefore the average of the score for Components 1A and 1B while the score for Component 1A is the average of the score for Subcomponents 1Ai and 1Aii.</p>\r\n                                <p>Additional research and analysis relative to the project can be found <a href="<?php echo home_url(); ?>/research">here</a>.</p>\r\n                            </article>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </section>\r\n                </div>\r\n                <a name="dimensions"></a>\r\n                    <section class="carousel dimensions">\r\n        <div class="row">\r\n            <header class="title-group">\r\n                <h2 id="six_dimensions">The Six Dimensions of Quality of Life Measures</h2>\r\n                <hr/>\r\n                <p>\r\n                    The Quality of Life Measures compiled data from a whole host of sources to compose this United States measurements. Various sources include (but are not limited to) the U.S. Census, the Bureau of Labor Statistics, Gallup, and the National Center for Educational Statistics.\r\n                </p>\r\n            </header>\r\n\r\n            <div class="slide-toggle clearfix">\r\n                <a href="#" class="us selected">U.S. Measurements</a><a href="#" class="world">World Measurements</a>\r\n            </div>\r\n\r\n            <ul class="slide-list">\r\n                <li class="slide us">\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns opportunity">\r\n                            <h3>Opportunity</h3>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Poverty<br />\r\n                                Employment<br />\r\n                                Community Vitality<br />\r\n                                Education</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns health_and_environment">\r\n                            <h3>Health &#038; Environment</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Physical Health<br />\r\n                                Mental Health<br />\r\n                                Environmental Health</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns freedom">\r\n                            <h3>Freedom</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Personal Freedom<br />\r\n                                Economic Freedom</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns community_and_relationships">\r\n                            <h3>Community &#038; Relationships</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Community Life<br />\r\n                                Family Life</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns living_standard">\r\n                            <h3>Living Standard</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Current Living Standard<br />\r\n                                Improvement in Living Standard</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns peace_and_security">\r\n                            <h3>Peace &#038; Security</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Violent Crime Rate<br />\r\n                                Property Crime Rate<br />\r\n                                Perceived Local Safety<br />\r\n                                Trust</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </li>\r\n                     <li class="slide world">\r\n\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns opportunity">\r\n                            <h3>Opportunity</h3>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Poverty<br />\r\n                                Employment<br />\r\n                                Community Basics<br />\r\n                                Entrepreneurship</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns health_and_environment">\r\n                            <h3>Health &#038; Environment</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Physical Health<br />\r\n                                Mental Health<br />\r\n                                Environmental Health</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns freedom">\r\n                            <h3>Freedom</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Political Freedom<br />\r\n                                Civil Liberties<br />\r\n                                Religious Freedom<br />\r\n                                Economic Freedom<br />\r\n                                Perceived Freedom</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns community_and_relationships">\r\n                            <h3>Community &#038; Relationships</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Community Life<br />\r\n                                Family Life</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns living_standard">\r\n                            <h3>Living Standard</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Current Living Standard<br />\r\n                                Improvement in Living Standard</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class="dimension large-4 medium-6 small-12 columns peace_and_security">\r\n                            <h3>Peace &#038; Security</h3>\r\n                            <br>\r\n                            <p>Categories:</p>\r\n                            <p>Violence and Ethnic Warfare<br />\r\n                                Human Rights Violations<br />\r\n                                Corruption in Business & Government<br />\r\n                                Trust in National Institutions<br />\r\n                                Law and Order<br />\r\n                                Bureaucracy Quality</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </li>\r\n                </ul>\r\n                <p>Learn more about the sources of these measurements.”</p>\r\n                <a class="btn flat gray download pdf variables" href="<?php echo get_template_directory_uri(); ?>/pdf/Quality_of_Life_Variables_US_Measures.pdf" target="_blank" style="background-image: url(&#39;<?php echo get_template_directory_uri(); ?>/images/icons/pdf.png&#39;);">Download U.S. Variables</a>\r\n\r\n            </div>\r\n        </section>\r\n            <div class="row">\r\n                <a name="glossary"></a>\r\n                <section class="glossary">\r\n                    <header class="title-group">\r\n                    <h2>Glossary</h2>\r\n                    <hr>\r\n                    </header>\r\n                    <div class="row">\r\n                        <div class="glossary-item-container large-12 medium-12 small-12 columns">\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Component</h3>\r\n                                <p>The different qualities of a particular dimension. For example, the components of the freedom dimension are civil liberties, economic freedom, political freedom, religious freedom, and perception of freedom.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Component Score</h3>\r\n                                <p>The value obtained from averaging the scores for subcomponents within a particular component for a country or U.S. state.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Dimension</h3>\r\n                                <p>One of the six key elements of Quality of Life Measures(i.e., Living Standard, Health &amp; Environment, Freedom, Opportunity, Community &amp; Relationships, or Peace &amp; Security) as defined by the Measures of Quality of Life.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Dimension Score</h3>\r\n                                <p>The value obtained from averaging the scores for components within a particular dimension for a country or U.S. state.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Happiness</h3>\r\n                                <p>The range of positive feelings, stretching from contentment to joy, that a person experiences.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Life Satisfaction</h3>\r\n                                <p>A person’s cognitive, evaluative reflection of that individual’s life as a whole.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Life ability</h3>\r\n                                <p>A measurement of an individual’s internal capacity to be happy and satisfied and his or her adeptness at taking advantage of the external environment.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Livability</h3>\r\n                                <p>A measurement of how the external, societal environment enables Quality of Life Measures.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Normalization</h3>\r\n                                <p>The method used to reconcile variables that are based on different units of measurement.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Objective Variables</h3>\r\n                                <p>Quantifiable social or economic variables that are based on specific standards and reported by outside observers.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Score</h3>\r\n                                <p>The normalized value used to estimate each variable. The variable scores are aggregated for subcomponents, components, and dimensions and result in the final measurement of the Quality of Life of a country or U.S. state.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Subcomponent</h3>\r\n                                <p>One of two or more factors of a component. For example, the Living Standard dimension consists of the two components of current living standard and improvement in living standard. The improvement in living standard component includes the 5-year growth in GDP and perceptions of improvement in living standard as subcomponents.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Subcomponent Score</h3>\r\n                                <p>The value obtained from averaging the scores for variables within a particular subcomponent for a country or U.S. state.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Subjective Variables</h3>\r\n                                <p>Variables that are individually perceived and obtained through self-reported methods.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Variable</h3>\r\n                                <p>One of many attributes used to characterize a certain aspect of the Quality of Life Measures of a country or U.S. state. There are 50 variables in the World measurements and 42 in the U.S. measurements.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Variable Score</h3>\r\n                                <p>The normalized value used to estimate each attribute of the Quality of Life Measures of a country or U.S. state.</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                            <div class="glossary-item">\r\n                                <h3>Quality of Life Measures Score</h3>\r\n                                <p>The value obtained from averaging the six dimension scores for a country or U.S. state.<br>\r\n                                Quality of Life Measures consists of the two underlying concepts of happiness and life satisfaction and emanates both from societal factors (livability) and from the internal personal dynamics that enable the individual to benefit from the societal environment (life ability).</p>\r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                </section>\r\n            </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n<script type="text/javascript">\r\n     jQuery.noConflict();\r\n        (function( $ ) {$(function() {$("#indices_id").addClass("current-menu-item");});\r\n      })(jQuery);\r\n</script>', 'Quality of Life Measures', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '224-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-03-10 11:52:56', '2015-03-10 11:52:56', '', 224, 'http://localhost/life-measures-wordpress/224-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
